<h3><strong>PLAN FUNNY ACTIVITIES</strong></h3>

<p>Once the foundation agreed on the main stops, we started to enrich the tour to make it more pleasant for students.<br>We included a day-trip to Como Lake (only one hour from Milan) with a boat tour and a trekking in the mountains around the lake, then a visit to Expo (the universal exhibition hosted in Milan from May to October 2015). From the city of Modena we planned a day-trip to Verona (2 hours away) to visit the famous Roman amphitheater and Romeo and Juliet’s balcony. Venice was not far either, so we could manage a day-trip there too: once there students could also visit a glass blowing factory in San Marco square, countless bridges and fascinating views.<br><strong>We did everything to find the right balance between educational and leisure activities, but also between free time and time spent with the rest of the class. </strong></p>

<p></p>

<h3><strong>WAIT FOR APPROVAL</strong></h3>

<p>Once the itinerary was completed, we submitted it to the educational foundation in order to proceed to the next step. They were really excited about our job, especially for the wise combination of education, culture and fun! Of course, it is an educational travel but we can not forget the importance of fun and free time, since after all it’s students’ trip to Italy!<br>We still needed to obtain the approval from the 2 professors, who has the right to make some changes. The response we received was completely unexpected. One of the professors said he wanted to stay only 2 nights in Milan, then 1 night in Florence, 1 in Sirmione to visit the Roman ruins, 2 nights in Verona, and 2 other nights in Venice. He also wanted to reach Pastrengo, near Verona, to visit a provider of paper-based packaging solutions, Smurfit Kappa. The first immediate problem that occurred was that Florence was 300 km away from the other cities, quite far from the itinerary established. Sleeping in Verona was problematic too, due to Verona Opera festival hold in July and the unlikelihood to find a hotel willing to host 40 students in that particular moment of the year. Moreover, sleeping in Venice would have been over the budget we were given.</p>

